05965nam a2200997Ia 9780228020530DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280205307 a10.1515/97802280205302doi  a(DE-B1597)679710  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV640b.M35 2024 7aSOC0660002bisacsh04a305.9/06914223/eng/202403251 aMartin-Shields, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUrban Refugees and Digital Technology :bReshaping Social, Political, and Economic Networks /cCharles Martin-Shields. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource :b7 diagrams, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Refugee and Forced Migration Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart One. Conceptualizing Technology and Urban Displacement in Theory and History -- t1 Urban Refugees in a Digital World -- t2 The Urban Context: Where Displacement and Digitalization Meet -- t3 Technological Change, New Displacement Patterns, and Urbanization -- t4 Digitalization and Urban Administration: Evolutions of Surveillance -- tPart Two. Contemporary Case Studies and the Digital Future of Urban Displacement -- t5 Methods in the Contemporary Context: Case Studies and Data Collection -- t6 Bogotá: ICT Access in the Neighbourhood -- t7 Kuala Lumpur: Time, Distance, and Legal Exclusion -- t8 Nairobi: Shifting Politics in a Digital Metropolis -- t9 Digitalization and Urban Displacement: Future Scenarios -- t10 The Future: Digitalization, Displacement, and New Urban Societies -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRefugees and displaced people are increasingly moving to cities around the world, seeking out the social, economic, and political opportunity that urban areas provide. Against this backdrop digital technologies are fundamentally changing how refugees and displaced people engage with urban landscapes and economies where they settle.Urban Refugees and Digital Technology draws on contemporary data gathered from refugee communities in Bogotá, Nairobi, and Kuala Lumpur to build a new theoretical understanding of how technological change influences the ways urban refugees contribute to the social, economic, and political networks in their cities of arrival. This data is presented against the broader history of technological change in urban areas since the start of industrialization, showing how displaced people across time have used technologized urban spaces to shape the societies where they settle. The case studies and history demonstrate how refugees’ interactions with environments that are often hostile to their presence spur novel adaptations to idiosyncratic features of a city’s technological landscape.A wide-ranging study across histories and geographies of urban displacement, Urban Refugees and Digital Technology introduces readers to the myriad ways technological change creates spaces for urban refugees to build rich political, social, and economic lives in cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRefugeeszColombiazBogotávCase studies. 0aRefugeeszColombiazBogotávCase studies. 0aRefugeeszKenyazNairobivCase studies. 0aRefugeeszMalaysiazKuala LumpurvCase studies. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspectszColombiazBogotávCase studies. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspectszColombiazBogotávCase studies. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspectszKenyazNairobivCase studies. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspectszMalaysiazKuala LumpurvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Refugees.2bisacsh  aBogota.  aColombia.  aCottonopo